{{Infobox book| | name = The Pocket Book of Boners | title_orig = | translator = | image =pocketbookboners498.jpg | image_size =200px | caption =1941 Readers' League of America printing | author = [[Dr. Seuss]] | cover_artist = Dr. Seuss | country = United States | language = English | series = | genre = [[Humor]] | publisher = [[The Viking Press]] | pub_date = June 23, 1931 | media_type = Print ([[paperback]]) | pages = 120 }}
'''''The Pocket Book of Boners''''' is a book illustrated by Theodor Seuss Geisel ([[Dr. Seuss]]), originally published as four separate books in 1931–32 by [[The Viking Press]]. In 1941, Readers' League of America compiled these four books and published the ''Pocket Book of Boners''.<ref name="1941note">Hansen, Harry (7 August 1941). [https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1144&dat=19410807&id=jXcbAAAAIBAJ&sjid=b0wEAAAAIBAJ&pg=1578,2787094 Craze for Boners Stages Comeback in Recent Book], ''The Pittsburgh Press'' (p. 29)</ref> It was one of the bestselling [[paperback]] books of [[World War II]], with 1.34 million copies in print by 1945.<ref>{{cite book |last=Davis |first=Kenneth C. |date=1984 |title=Two-Bit Culture: The Paperbacking of America |url= |location= |publisher=Houghton Mifflin |page=79 |isbn=0-395-35535-4}}</ref> At the time of its writing, the term "boner" was commonly used to mean a silly mistake, without any sexual connotation.
''The Pocket Book of Boners'' contains 22 illustrations of [[wikt:boner|boner]]s by [[Dr. Seuss]]. The rest of the volume consists of short jokes and humorous observations with most being no more than four lines long, and is notable for its early examples of [[Dr. Seuss]]' illustration style.{{Citation needed|date=July 2011}}.
==Boners series== The first book was released in February 1931. A short positive review in ''[[The New York Times]]'' described Dr. Seuss's illustrations as "hilarious."<ref name="nyt1">(March 1, 1931). [https://select.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=F70D1FFE3D591B728DDDA80894DB405B818FF1D3&action=click&module=Search&region=searchResults%230&version=&url=http%3A%2F%2Fquery.nytimes.com%2Fsearch%2Fsitesearch%2F%23%2Fboners%2Babingdon%2F Schoolboy Wisdom], ''[[The New York Times]]''</ref> The pseudonym "Alexander Abingdon" was used as the author of the series, which was originally released in order as follows.
*''Boners'' (102 p.)(copyright February 7, 1931) (illustrated by Dr. Seuss) * ''More Boners'' (copyright April 31, 1931) (illustrated by Dr. Seuss) *''Still More Boners'' (copyright August 4, 1931)(illustrated by [[Virginia Huget]]) *''Prize Boners for 1932'' (copyright March 4, 1932) (illustrated by Virginia Huget).<ref name="cata">[https://books.google.com/books?id=q6shAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA2375&lpg=PA2375&dq#v=onepage&q&f=false Catalog of Copyright Entries. New Series: 1931, Part 1], 2375 (U.S. Library of Congress)</ref><ref name="cata2">[https://books.google.com/books?id=LKEhAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA193&dq=#v=onepage&q&f=false Catalog of Copyright Entries. New Series: 1932, Part 1], p. 1207 (U.S. Library of Congress)</ref>
Many compilations of ''Boners'' content were subsequently released, including ''The Omnibus Boners'' (1931) and ''The 2nd Boners Omnibus'' (1938) (pictures by Galdone).<ref name="2ndbonus">[https://books.google.com/books?id=Gg8jAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA519&lpg=PA519&dq=%22#v=onepage&q&f=false Catalog of Copyright Entries. New Series: 1938-1939, Part 1], p. 519</ref>
